    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-12-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-12-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="644"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d644">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.5431/276</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Chief of the Division of Trade
                        Agreements</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Grady</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-12-16">December 16,
                            1935</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I saw the President this morning by appointment and secured his approval of the
                    attached schedule on watches.<note n="31" xml:id="d644fn31">Not printed.</note>
                    This schedule calls for an average reduction of 33.8 percent as against the 29.8
                    percent provided in our last offer to the Swiss. The President approved this
                    reduction because of the arrangements with the Swiss by which smuggling will be
                    greatly reduced, if not eliminated, and of the provision for the reduction in
                    the duty on parts, which will be helpful to the domestic manufacturers. He urged
                    that, if possible, we get, after the agreement is announced, some statement from
                    watch interests approving the arrangement regarding the smuggling provisions and
                    reductions of duties on watches in the Swiss agreement.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Henry F. Grady</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
